'''Superhuman''' qualities are qualities that exceed those found in [[human]]s. 

The ''[[Übermensch]]'' or "Superman" was postulated by [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] as a type of supreme, ultra-[[aristocracy|aristocratic]] achievement which becomes possible in the transcendence of modernity, morals or nihilism.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nietzsche |first1=Friedrich |authorlink1=Friedrich Nietzsche |title=Ecce Homo: How One Becomes What One Is & The Antichrist: A Curse on Christianity. |date=2007 |publisher=Algora Publishing |location=New York |isbn=9780875862835 |page=41 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xx6IfcqRvbwC&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en |chapter=Why I Write Such Good Books |quote=The word "Superman" as the designation for a type of the highest successfulness as opposed to "modern" men, to "good" men, to Christians and other nihilists.}}</ref>

In [[transhumanism]] and [[futurology]], superhuman abilities are the technological aim either of [[human enhancement]] by [[Genetic engineering|genetic modification]] or [[Cyberware|cybernetic implants]] or of future [[Superintelligence|superhuman artificial intelligence]].

Speculation about human nature and the possibilities of both [[human enhancement]] and future [[human evolution]] have made superhumans a popular subject of [[science fiction]].

Superhuman abilities are also associated with the genre of [[superhero]]es. 

==Human enhancement and advancement==
{{Further|Human enhancement|Transhumanism|Posthuman}}
Human enhancement is an attempt to temporarily or permanently overcome the current limitations of the [[human body]] through natural or artificial means. Human enhancement may be through the use of technological means to select or alter human characteristics and capacities, whether or not the alteration results in characteristics and capacities that lie beyond the existing human range.

Some [[bioethicist]]s restrict the term to the non-therapeutic application of [[Human enhancement#Technologies|specific technologies]] — [[Neurotechnology|neuro-]], [[cyberware|cyber-]], [[gene therapy|gene-]] and [[nanomedicine|nano-technologies]] — to [[human biology]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hughes |first1=James |authorlink1=James Hughes (sociologist) |title=Human Enhancement on the Agenda |journal=[[Institute for Ethics and Emerging Technologies]] |date=October 2004 |url=https://ieet.org/index.php/IEET2/more/hughes20041101 |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Pete |authorlink1=Pete Moore (science writer) |title=Enhancing Me: The Hope and the Hype of Human Enhancement |date=2008 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |location=[[Chichester]] |isbn=047069999X}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2018}}

According to transhumanist thinkers, a [[posthuman]] is a hypothetical [[future]] being "''whose basic capacities so radically exceed those of present humans as to be no longer unambiguously [[human]] by our current standards.''"<ref>{{cite web |author1=[[Nick Bostrom]] |title=The Transhumanist FAQ |url=http://www.transhumanism.org/resources/FAQv21.pdf |website=Humanity+ |accessdate=August 27, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231225013/http://www.transhumanism.org/resources/FAQv21.pdf |archivedate=December 31, 2006 |date=October 2003}}</ref>

==Artificial beings==
{{Further|Artificial intelligence|Multi-agent system}}
''Superhuman'' is one of the stages in classification of [[progress in artificial intelligence]] where an entity of artificial intelligence performs better than most humans do in a specific task.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} Examples of where computers have achieved superhuman performance include [[Backgammon]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tesauro |first1=Gerald |title=Temporal difference learning and TD-Gammon |journal=Communications of the ACM |date=1 March 1995 |volume=38 |issue=3 |pages=58–68 |doi=10.1145/203330.203343}}</ref> [[Computer bridge|Bridge]],{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} [[Chess]],{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} [[Reversi]],{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} [[Scrabble]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sheppard |first1=Brian |title=World-Championship-Caliber Scrabble |journal=Artificial Intelligence |date=January 2002 |volume=134 |issue=1-2 |pages=241–275 |doi=10.1016/S0004-3702(01)00166-7}}</ref> [[Go (game)|Go]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Metz |first1=Cade |title=Google's AI Wins Fifth And Final Game Against Go Genius Lee Sedol |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/03/googles-ai-wins-fifth-final-game-go-genius-lee-sedol/ |website=WIRED |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |date=March 15, 2016}}</ref> and [[Jeopardy!]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rashid |first1=Fahmida Y. |title=IBM's Watson Ties for Lead on Jeopardy but Makes Some Doozies |url=http://www.eweek.com/c/a/IT-Infrastructure/IBMs-Watson-Ties-for-Lead-on-Jeopardy-but-Makes-Some-Doozies-237890/ |website=eWEEK |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |date=February 14, 2011}}</ref>

